What is the difference between CNAME and Alias?

CNAME -> map one domain name to another domain name 

Alias ( specific to Route 53 ) -> points domain name to an AWS resource - like a load balancer or s3 bucket 
- Can be used a root domain example.com / blog.example.com (sub domain)
- Free & doesn’t count as a DNS lookup ( cost efficient )
- Native health checks - more resilience 


What are Alias records in AWS? 

Maps a domain name directly to an AWS resource ONLY 
+ when AWS resource changes IP address , route 53 is able to update the alias to keep mapping it to that resource 

Alias record is always a type of A/AAAA record - so IPv4 and IPv6 
- Can’t set a TTL as it’s auto changing if needed to map domain to AWS resource  


Route 53 - Alias Record Targets 

You can set a chain of Aliases to the same AWS resource 
    - Example.com  → CloudFront 
    - Blog.example.com → CloudFront 
    - Mapping different domain names to the same AWS resource 

Also can map to AWS : Elastic Load Balancer , API gateway , S3 , VPC endpoints , Global accelerator, Elastic beanstalk env’s 
- But can’t set alias for a EC2 DNS






Route 53 - A / AAAA records ?

DNS records that map domain names to an IPv4 address 

Each record contains : 

→ domain name / sub domain name 
→ record type = A or AAAA
→ TTL - time to live = how long a DNS resolver caches your record before refreshing 
→ Routing policy - determines how DNS response to queries 
→ Route 53 supports DNS records type = A , AAAA , CNAME , NS , MX 



Route 53 - Record Types ?

A = maps to domain name to IPv4 
AAAAA = maps domain name to IPv6
CNAME = maps one domain to another domain - www.example.com = example.com  alias 
NS ( Nameserver) = name server for hosted zone and controls how traffic is routed for a domain ?****



Route 53 - Time To Live ?

TTL is mandatory for DNS records except alias 

High TTL - caches the response (typically an IP)
   + Good because it means less traffic will hit web server + route 53 for response 
- Bad because what if the response is outdated 


Low TTL -
- Bad because more traffic will hit route 53 and web server + more cost 

  + Good because responses are outed for less time 
  + easy to change records (updating ip’s etc )



Route 53 - Health checks ?

Health checks monitor the availability of endpoints / resources 
- If an endpoint / resource fails check repeatedly = marked as unhealthy = DNS failover 


HTTP/s health checks are used to test web endpoints - for status codes 
TCP health checks monitor whether a port is open ( useful for non HTTP service )

You can check AWS resources by tying AWS Cloudwatch alarms to route 53 health checks 
- Same for Amazon RDS directly to check database availability - if unhealthy = DNS failover = auto shift traffic to healthy alternative backup (server ,region , site etc )

DNS failover can be triggered by health check failures , routing traffic to healthy endpoints 
Health checks can be public or private and check internal resources too 
They run at intervals and must meet success / failure thresholds 




Route 53 - Routing (responding) policies in AWS ?

This defines how route 53 will respond to DNS queries 
- Its not the same “routing” like a ALB which routes traffic 
- DNS doesn’t route traffic only responds to DNS queries 


1. Simple routing
- Same static response
- If there are multiple values are returned for a query one will be chosen at random

———————— 
2. weighted routing = control the percentage % off the request that goes to each resource 
- 60 % to endpoint 1 and 40 % to endpoint 2 
- If all records have a weight of 0 , then all records returned equally 
- DNS records that we splitting traffic between have to be the same name and type ( have to be under the same domain “example.com records”)
- Weights don’t have to equal 100%
- Traffic % = weight of specific record / sum of all weights for all records 

Uses cases : load balancing between regions or end points  , gradual deployment 

—————————

3. Latency based routing = Routing to the resource that has the least latency close to us 
- Helpful when latency is important of user 
- Latency is based on traffic between users and AWS regions 

i.e - Germany users may need be redirected to the US ( if that’s the lowest latency )
+ can be associated with health checks ( has a failover capability )


——————————

4. Geolocation routing = route based on user’s location ( location specific content ) 
- Configure based of user location (county , city , state etc )
- Create a default record - if no match country is found user still receives response 
- Can be associated with health checks - route 53 will monitor if the resource is healthy and reliable endpoints ( if not healthy R53 will choose an alternative )

Use cases = website localisation , restrict content distribution , load balancing 


———————— 

5. Geo proximity Routing = routing based on your resources based on geographical location of users and resources 

- Have ability to shift more traffic to resources based  on the defined bias 
- Use Route 53 traffic flow to change size of geographical region and specific bias values 
- To expand ( 1-99 ) - more traffic to the resource 
- To shrink (-1 to 99 ) - less traffic to the resource 
- Resources can be AWS resources ( Specify AWS region)
- or non AWS resources ( Specify Latitude and longitude )
 

Client - dns resolver - route 53 - routing policy and checks resource locations  - returns  ip of the closest resource 

————————-

6. IP based routing = route 53 uses requester IP address to determine which endpoint / resource they should route them to 
- CIDR blocks define where to send users per server / endpoint  for example 

Use cases : optimise performance , ensuring compliance based on countries , routing to internal networks and network costs 


————————

7 . Multi value routing = that responds multi healthy multiple values / resources / endpoints - client then can choose 

- If one fails they can choose another - high availability and failover + balancing load ( auto shifting traffic if something goes wrong ) spreading traffic when all is healthy = getting multiple ip’s 
- Can be associated with health checks 
- Up to 8 healthy records are retuned for each multi value query 
- Not a substitute for a having a elastic load balancer 


Failover routing = provide a backup if primary fails 


